You'd expect the author to spend time on the husband's character, showing through his speech and actions how deeply he loves his wife, and similarly, you'd expect the heroine to demonstrate through various ways how much his presence transformed and enriched her life (especially if the story later outright states it). A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to be emotionally invested in his fate and provide insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, the depth of their bond, clues about her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams as reflected through his eyes, and so forth. You would mourn his death with her, thus becoming more connected to the heroine.

In short, you'd expect substance on the simple storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that substance. (*glances at metaphor, sighs, and continues*) Sometimes it's tempting to rush through certain things. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, is now the night manager of a gas station, has been married twice, no children, enjoys fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first was a "live" broadcast from NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife. Her name wasn't mentioned, but his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mugshot, and he looked quite sinister. They spent about two minutes on this developing story, only mentioning that he had stabbed her multiple times and was arrested. I felt they allocated an appropriate amount of time to this story.

The second story was about an early morning shooting involving an 18-year-old named Travis Buyers. He was critically injured in the Sharon Woods area, and no arrests or suspects had been made at the time. The SWAT team was investigating. This story seemed brief, possibly because the individual was a "black" man or it occurred in a black neighborhood. I've noticed over the years that minorities tend to be overlooked when they become victims of crime. If a "white" child or adult is kidnapped, missing, or a crime victim, the media goes into a frenzy; but if it's a minority, it's fortunate if it's even mentioned.

The next story was about a bullet hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. Details were provided about where they thought the incident took place. It was determined that a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle hit the helicopter. Crime Stoppers are offering a five-thousand-dollar reward for information leading to the shooter's arrest.

The following story was about the forecast of rain and thunderstorms for Saturday afternoon. They said temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The segment was short, but they used it as a "teaser" to keep viewers tuned in.

They also reported a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They described the suspect as a dark-skinned black man wearing a hoodie. He was said to be about six feet tall and weighed around one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they spent an unusual amount of time emphasizing his race and how dark his skin was.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin. He was convicted of conspiring to distribute large amounts of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. One curious detail was that instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison, they said "300" months. I'm not sure what the angle was, whether it was to make it sound harsher or something else. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, which I didn't think was particularly relevant to the story.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a type of security designed to track an index, commodity, or a basket of assets like an index fund, but it is more flexible and trades on an exchange like a stock. An ETF offers the diversification benefits of an index fund, combined with the advantages of individual stock ownership, such as the ability to short sell, buy on margin, and purchase as few as one share in any transaction. While these benefits are highly attractive, the expense ratios of ETFs are much lower than those of average mutual funds. Unfortunately, there are some downsides, such as the need to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, similar to what you would pay for a stock order. Another advantage of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available. Although these benefits are clear, it is always wise for a savvy financial investor to assess whether the stated benefits, like diversification, genuinely exist and to what extent. For this purpose, we will examine the ETF IHF and compare it to the top 10 holdings that comprise the ETF to determine whether the benefits of owning a single ETF are close to those of owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks, and also whether there are better configurations of the same stocks that could offer a more optimal Sharpe ratio or return.

To evaluate the ETF, including every holding would become quite cumbersome, so we have decided to include only the top ten holdings, which account for 63.58% of all the assets in the ETF. Below are the top 10 holdings and their percentage of total assets.

To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate the contribution of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio were entirely made up of these 10 stocks in the proportion that the ETF has established through their holdings. The calculations of Beta and return are included in the chart below.

From the chart above, it is evident that the return of a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF, representing a 16% increase in returns. It is also evident that the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF as a whole. The results so far suggest that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could offer a higher return with a lower beta. However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.

To assess whether these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is determined and normalized to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Referring to Figure 17, there was a sharp drop in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. This was somewhat disheartening, and it's hard to pinpoint the exact cause. As winter arrives on the New England campus, there's a noticeable decrease in people commuting by bicycle or on foot, which might partly explain the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester when everyone is busy finishing schoolwork and processing grades, causing many to overlook filling out the commuter log. Additionally, December brings the busy holiday season and a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many do not need to come to campus at all. Classes resume in late January for the spring semester, possibly explaining the low number of logs for that month. However, none of this fully accounts for the low submissions in February. It's possible that any project like this experiences an initial burst of energy and excitement that naturally wanes. To counter this trend, we initiated the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special campaign aimed at reinvigorating the initiative, which indeed led to an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one challenge we faced was maintaining project momentum amidst a natural decline in engagement and the specific issue of holiday and semester breaks in higher education.

Another challenge for this project, or any alternative commuting project, is the simple fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving. This is deeply ingrained in our culture. Therefore, it is essential to provide incentives for engaging in alternative commuting modes. We offered numerous prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. However, it would have been interesting to see how larger prizes might have influenced participation—such as offering a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This might have helped combat the dip in engagement experienced by the project. The nature of the prizes didn't really change during the project. However, if the prizes had increased in value over the course of the project, it might have helped. The gift cards seemed more than adequate at the project's outset, but had we announced in December the addition of a couple of bicycles, and then in January the addition of a hybrid or electric car, participation and engagement might have increased rather than decreased.

When exploring the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I decided to watch all the trick films, which numbered fifteen between 1895 and 1901. These films typically employ creative editing to create illusions. My study of these films focused on describing the poetics of most trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier traits in some of the later ones. Generally, trick films at the turn of the century are set-bound, framed within a frontal proscenium, feature no camera movement, use long and medium shots, and adhere to the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, some films in the early twentieth century dared to break these norms by introducing elements like multiple shots. 

One of the most noticeable common features is that these trick films are shot within a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films, rooted in theater, and for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. A limitation of using the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side and do not walk towards or away from the camera. For example, in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), the actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even when they leave the frame, the camera does not follow. 

The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-up shots are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This draws from the theater and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the stage's borders. As in most early films, the actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur. 

Typically, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative use of trick films; most focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts, with little story. However, note that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single "shot" may actually be several joined together to produce the illusion of apparition or disappearing. Look carefully at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A closer inspection reveals the moment when the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, even though conceptually, the whole film is one continuous shot to the viewer.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is, as Ian Watt describes in "The Rise of the Gothic Novel," an oxymoron for "Old-New." The Gothic style has been criticized, praised, accused of lacking real depth, and commended for its "terrible sublime" quality (Burke). The first "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's "The Castle of Otranto," combined ideas from both "ancient and modern" romances to form the proto-Gothic genre and create a new literary expression. Walpole used "old" theatrical elements and "new" nature mimicry in "modern" novels to present what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws on many elements of medieval gothic theater, architecture, and traditions. Even at the time of "The Castle of Otranto's" publication, the term "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and periods, and was considered archaic or unsophisticated compared to "modern" societal and literary "advancements." The blend of the theatrical "Gothic" with the new novel format (which offers readers a more personal view of characters' psychology) is what allowed Gothic to endure for so long and appear both obsolete and novel to readers far removed in time from the original writing.

One of the most distinct Gothic ideas in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, the process of training a proper knight, is preserved and transformed in the original Gothic novel, "The Castle of Otranto." Chivalry is crucial to Gothic writers because it represented the classic knight—brave, honorable, competent—and the perceived lack of that ideal in society according to writers like Walpole. Through chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" becomes idealized and romanticized (hinting at Gothic's evolution towards Romanticism) and is used to attempt to improve the present. Walpole, writing "The Castle of Otranto" during politically troubled times and despairing over the future, may have begun to think that the supposed morality and inherent "goodness" present in the Gothic era had somehow been lost in those individuals making up contemporary society. In his writing, this idea is evident in several characters, such as Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, the reader sees he embodies many chivalric traits, described as:

His description includes many traditional chivalric images; Frederic is primarily a prince who has suffered, been profoundly affected by tragedy to the point of departure, and is currently thought to have been killed by infidels. The image of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is, of course, exaggerated, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management involves the flow of processes that move goods from the customer order stage through raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. The term was coined by consultant Keith Oliver in 1982. He described it as the overall process of planning, implementing, and controlling activities in the supply chain to meet customer needs quickly and efficiently. There are six key elements in a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these elements to deliver the best customer service.

Production is the first step in the supply chain process and serves as the foundation for the entire system. This stage outlines when, why, where, and how everything will be produced. Managers need to understand what customers want, and they can do this by analyzing the market, which is the primary indicator of customer demand. Once they have understood the market and customer demands, they decide on what products to produce and the quantities. After these decisions, they choose the production site and plant that best meets the volume and quality needs while considering customer satisfaction. Once the location is set, the focus shifts to scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Production is crucial in the supply chain process, and every detail matters. Mistakes in planning can cost the company time and money. For instance, in my experience working at Wal-Mart and Target, both had detailed processes for every business aspect, from employee uniforms to receiving goods, which ensured smooth operations without confusion.

The second key element in supply chain management is supply. Supply involves strategic decisions to determine a facility's core capabilities, with outsourcing partnerships developing from these decisions. A company might have multiple production divisions for a single product, each with different equipment, workers, and skills. Managers must choose the best division for each product process, and they may decide to outsource work to other companies. The main reason for outsourcing is to create velocity—providing quality and flexibility while reducing or maintaining low cost levels.

Victorian novels are known for their detailed attention and focus on the period's aristocracy. However, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights" deviate from this tradition. Both novels incorporate elements of mystery and the bizarre, which were uncommon in the literature of the time, enhancing character depth and offering insights into their motivations and emotions.

“Now, a multitude of bewildering and confusing thoughts flooded his mind. He seemed to still be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing angrily: their words echoed in his ears; and when he regained his focus… he found himself talking to them… Suddenly, he was startled by the sound of gunfire; loud cries and shouts rose into the air; lights flashed before his eyes, and everything was noise and chaos as if an unseen hand hurriedly carried him away. Through all these rapid visions, there was a vague, uneasy awareness of pain that incessantly tormented him.” (Dickens, 220)

These novels often use mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, though the content and function differ in each specific case. In "Oliver Twist," these strange occurrences often reveal insights into Oliver’s inner struggles, what pains him, and his understanding of the true nature of events around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in Chapter 28, he vividly relives it as if in a dream while struggling to find help. This passage highlights Oliver's lack of control over unfolding events and his dire health situation, evident through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting overwhelms him, numbing all his senses, so he does not notice the "unseen hand" that carries him away; he experiences his despair anew, detached from the shock of pain, with the pain now constant and linked to fear rather than surprise. As Oliver is overwhelmed, the question arises of whose will brought about his misfortune, as it was certainly not his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, unable to even attempt to influence an event’s outcome, even when his life is at risk. A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also suggested, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him to accept this despair, affecting his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have at least made some effort for the sake of his own life.

“The day passed – day! There was no day; it vanished as soon as it came – and night came again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours.

A few years ago, I worked in an after-school program tutoring elementary-aged students. I tried to assist them in any subject they struggled with, but my strengths were in English and reading. I was asked by an instructor to help a young boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade) who was having significant trouble with reading. It seemed to me something was wrong; he had the most peculiar problems. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, while others were completely off, which was very strange. I was sure he was of Latino descent, yet the boy spoke perfect English. We faced difficulties until I met his mother. While supervising a few remaining kids when the rest of the after-school group went on a field trip, his mother came in. She spoke no English, only Spanish. Despite my limited Spanish skills (I was just learning), we managed to communicate. It then struck me: Adrian could read well, he just didn't know the English alphabet very well. I'm not sure if this realization helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier issue in schools, especially here in California. It also shows that the problem isn't always as obvious as we might think. Even a child who speaks perfect English can find reading it to be a major obstacle. I think everyone agrees this problem exists, so what can we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was simple: tutoring in English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciation. But for many children who barely speak English, the solution is more complex. There is no single answer. Dual language systems, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—none of these alone will fix the problem. The key is to integrate all of these approaches!

First of all, the dual language system is a great idea. Not only for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically." There is a lot of fear about this idea, that it's a waste of resources and that most children will gain no benefit. But that's not true. If we applied these programs as a rule in the classroom, rather than an exception, all children would benefit. How do we achieve this? Should we require all teachers to be bilingual? No. That would be unreasonable and slightly unrealistic. However, I do think there's no reason we can't have special aids, tutors, or whatever you want to call them, who are bilingual.

From the time we are children, most of us are told that there is something greater than ourselves, beyond our comprehension. Some are sent to Sunday school to learn about it, while others go to temples or search within themselves for answers. Many of us readily accept the religions handed down by our parents. However, some reject them entirely, denying that there can be anything beyond what we know in our egocentric universe. We might adopt one set of values, only to change our minds later. Whatever path we choose, we journey to define a part of ourselves through our unique spiritual perspectives. We search for a light in the darkness to guide us from the shadows into the sunshine.

"A cardinal," my father replied when I asked him about his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, listening to the rain pounding on the tin roof above as we smoked. The gutters carried the rain down, drowning the plants at the porch's edge. He gazed into the rain, a look that seemed half searching, half remembering. He had grown thinner over the months, his clothes hanging limply on him. His hair was sparser than I remembered. Still, he gazed into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, frightened, unable to discuss with my father how much I would miss him, because talking about it would make it too real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair a little closer, and joined him in watching the June twilight rain.

My father passed away that December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation did not ease his suffering but kept him alive a few more months beyond the doctors' predictions; I couldn't define the value when he only suffered longer. I wondered what kind of God would do this. Alone at night, I said no prayers. If God existed, I thought, he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I didn't want to watch him pass from this life to another. So I didn't. I couldn't watch the life that created me come to an end. I wanted to remember my father for how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than they did, better than his family, and knew he wouldn't want his only child to be a spectator at his death. I curled up in my bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and fervent supporter of Republicanism. Though primarily an agriculturalist, his dedication and outspokenness on personal freedom and government issues were well-known due to his career in politics. His commitment to an agrarian system underpinned nearly all his views on government. His efforts to preserve and encourage what he considered the most excellent career colored his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

John Taylor believed the United States had a unique chance to create an ideal system since there was no native tradition to constrain government creators, thereby allowing for self-governance. He strongly believed in the natural rights of man and their interdependence—if one is denied, all will fail, diminishing the value of those remaining. Thus, these rights should be beyond the government's reach. He argued that the "state of nature" allowed those with physical strength and malevolent intelligence to benefit, but in a civilized society, this should not be so.

To build this ideal society, Taylor believed a government must account for the inherent good and evil within humans. He was firm in his dualistic morality views, claiming, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human." He defined good principles as those protecting private property, enhancing agriculture, and discouraging capitalism, believing that a government founded on good principles would function fairly regardless of its administration, inevitably led by greed and self-interest. Self-interest, he believed, motivated all human actions but was only deemed evil when leading to sub-societies living at others' expense. A good government was necessary to control man's natural evil, with careful monitoring to prevent bad principles.

Like many staunch Republicans of his era, Taylor advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He desired a highly limited Federal government, with no more rights or powers than explicitly stated in the Constitution. He recognized that an extensive Federal government was expensive and likely despotic. However, he believed a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous, as it could easily become corrupt without reference to the writers' intent. Furthermore, he regarded the Declaration of Independence as the true charter of the United States, as it more explicitly described the country as a group of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

I looked downwards, my mind blankly processing the view before me. Unemotionally and silently, with a practiced awareness, I studied the scene without connecting it to any abstract understanding. Thoughts flowed in and out of my mind almost as quickly as they appeared. My consciousness worked so smoothly and cleanly that it seemed I had no real thoughts, just an active and fluid experience of what I was seeing.

Once, following advice from an artist I worked with, I bought a book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I had wanted to learn to draw since I was six, and this book taught everything from understanding a pencil to how the brain interprets lines. One technique it teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wishes to study, transforming a detailed scene — like a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen connected to a dining room — into a simple, easily grasped image of the bowl of fruit on a plain surface.

At the time, staring at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't mentally project that artist's frame. I was so overwhelmed, so in awe, that I could only stand and gaze in wonder. Picasso had his blue period, Monet loved greenery, and the Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any aspirations of viewing my perspective as worthy of the title "Artistic," then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story: "Work in Brown."

My fingertips touched my chosen artistic tool lightly, muscles tensing and relaxing as my hand moved through space, shaping my mind’s will in what could have been the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear. Flakes of matter broke away and vanished. Muscles tensed, jerking a little faster and more anxiously the second time, my hand hit the toilet handle again. The offensive brown package refused to move, stuck at the bottom like a slug.

Loosely gripping the mop, feet a foot apart, green tie uncomfortably knotted around my neck, I frowned slightly as I looked at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter left as a message for the unfortunate souls cleaning the bathrooms at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more moments of tranquil introspection, then my hand moved towards the wall to the right, grabbing the end of the toilet paper, wrapping itself until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand slowly dipped into the bowl, like a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teenagers are increasingly dying while driving. Various factors combine to form this deadly statistical trend for young American drivers. The National Institutes of Health explains that part of the issue is that the teenage brain is not yet ready to handle the dangers of driving. Lack of experience also lies at the core of the problem, leading to more fatal accidents, higher rates of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and off-road incidents.

Teens perform worse when traveling with peers—a fact known to anyone with common sense, as they do this regularly. A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center showed a correlation between the age of passengers and the number of traffic accidents.

California and other states have tried to increase teen driving safety by requiring provisional licenses, which limit driving hours and prohibit other minors as passengers.

In my opinion, however, provisional licenses are stopgap measures. The real issue is that the youngest drivers, as a group, are statistically unable to handle the risks and responsibilities adequately. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes that even at 18, one is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research suggests a common desire among those under 19-20 to take risks for the thrill. Thus, delaying driving until the thrill-seeking tendency subsides makes sense. If we continue to issue licenses to young teens, we will see ongoing deadly accidents, with death tolls possibly reaching staggering numbers in the next few years. By 2010, the children of the Baby Boomer generation will be eligible to drive, with millions of new teen drivers ready to hit the road.

Legislation addressing this issue would be straightforward. Schools could continue to offer driver's education to start the learning process for future drivers, but no one under 18 would operate a motor vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued before granting a full license, with a certain amount of practical training required. The specific hours required could be based on the current requirements of most states (e.g., in California, it's 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult). Given that deadly statistics for teen drivers come from all states, a uniform national legislation on this issue would be reasonable—and I believe effective—in protecting teens nationwide.

The legislation I propose is by no means a novel idea.

This paper explores three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Initially, a brief definition of the disorder is given. Following that, the diagnosis process is explained, highlighting common traits or "red flags." Finally, the paper concludes with strategies for how a teacher in a mainstream classroom can support a student with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), refers to the efficiency and effectiveness with which the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. Specifically, (C)AP involves the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiological activities that support this processing and generate electrophysiological auditory potentials (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This means it is a disorder where the central nervous system (i.e., the brain) fails to adequately process what is heard. Individuals with CAPD have normal hearing and are not considered "hearing impaired"; rather, the brain region responsible for translating auditory inputs, such as distinguishing words or separating conversations from background noise, does not function typically.

The earliest reference to the disorder now known as CAPD dates back to the mid-1950s, when it was termed "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), as researchers were assessing children with communication disorders. The Italian research group of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for such children in 1954. In 1961, Kimura introduced dichotic testing and developed a model to explain the central auditory nervous system (CANS) physiology underlying dichotic perception (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference in 1977 spurred research on children with CAPD.

CAPD manifests in various ways: the affected individual may struggle to localize or hear sounds in space; may find it hard to differentiate between two or more "acoustic events" (sound occurrences); may be unable to recognize sound patterns or detect changes in speech (such as sarcasm based on tone); one sound may be masked by a subsequent sound; they may lack the ability to synthesize auditory cues (meaningfully interpret them to take action); and may struggle to identify the sequence of auditory information (Ferre).

To diagnose CAPD, patients must be screened through "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on auditory function tests," which may be conducted by "audiologists, speech-language pathologists, psychologists, and others using various measures to evaluate auditory-related skills" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This can involve questionnaires and surveys, and observing auditory behaviors, including patient responses to specific stimuli. Currently, there is no single tool or test consistently used with a high success rate for diagnosis, and no known cause of the disorder. Many tests present multiple simultaneous auditory stimuli and ask patients to distinguish specific items, such as a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests involve recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to these signals.

In my pursuit of education in social work, I plan to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected and to support troubled families. I bring values to the social work field such as service, respect, ethics, and a commitment to improving relationships and my professional skills. These core values are not only important to social workers but also hold personal significance for me.

I have always wanted to help others, but I was uncertain about the career path to choose. During my high school and college years, I saw many individuals deny their problems and some adopt less than ideal coping strategies. Because of these experiences, I decided to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology. Still unsure about my career direction, I took a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy on her couch. She explained he was trying to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I found out he had called the police to his parents' home. To see if I could help, I went to his parents' house. There, I privately expressed my concerns to the police and mentioned I had just graduated with a Psychology degree from Piedmont College. The police asked me to talk to the parents since the law couldn't help the teenager. When I asked the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and made excuses for their son's "manipulative" behavior in involving external parties for "simple" disputes. This experience led me to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with "simple" family disputes.

Social justice is another essential value in social work. As a society, we claim to value individuals and mourn those we have lost. Yet, the idea of the "individual" in society often follows outdated traditions rather than true uniqueness. If society mourns lost individuals, why do we strive to be like "everyone else?" I am an individual and dislike limiting myself to fit in with others. Throughout high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever possible: dyeing my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothes that matched my personality, piercing my ears beyond traditional norms, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and opposing racism and discrimination whenever I saw it. I believe in social justice and will continue to stand against social injustice.

The paper discusses the biological and sociocultural models related to insomnia. The biological model examines genetic information and medical aspects of health, while the sociocultural model considers environmental relationships and their implications for race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review of insomnia explores these models and explains each piece of related research to better illustrate the models. It critiques the studies and their findings, highlighting specific strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep disorders can be classified as primary sleep disorders, those related to other mental disorders, or those due to other issues. Primary sleep disorders include insomnia and parasomnias, while those related to other mental disorders are associated with Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other sleep disorders may result from medical complications or substance intake. Dyssomnias include: primary insomnia, primary hypersomnia, narcolepsy, breathing-related sleep disorder, circadian rhythm sleep disorder, and dyssomnia not otherwise specified (NOS). Primary insomnia involves insufficient or poorly maintained sleep, while primary hypersomnia refers to difficulty staying awake, both lasting at least one month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM. Dyssomnias focus on initiating and maintaining sleep, whereas parasomnias are linked to behavioral abnormalities and/or physiological events. Parasomnias include nightmare disorder, sleep terror disorder, sleepwalking disorder, and parasomnias not otherwise specified. Sleep disorders related to other mental disorders involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (clinical disorders) or Axis II (personality disorders or mental retardation). This review primarily focuses on insomnia and, to some extent, on primary sleep disorders in general concerning biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspects of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin regulate sleep and wakefulness. A study using mice found phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons responsible for sleep/wake states. Activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. Inhibition of its firing can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). These findings suggest that mouse models can be applied to human studies, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for the GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence of this receptor could affect one's ability to achieve adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication is that if this phenotype is inherited, it could regulate sleep, and alterations in the receptor would naturally disrupt an individual's sleep. This could negatively impact aspects of life such as education, career, and daily activities that require focus on monotonous tasks.

I have been studying at University Park for about two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. For many people, including myself, getting around campus can be challenging. During my freshman year, I lived in an East Halls dormitory, which is nearly at the easternmost edge of campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my place in Stuart Hall to classes in distant locations like the Willard building could take up to 25 minutes, especially in the often inclement weather of State College. A conversation with an alum, who is not much older than me, revealed that not long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the campus by large expanses of unused land. Today, that empty space is filled with sports fields, large new buildings like the new Creamery and health services building, and surrounded by apartments. As campus continues to expand, moving from one place to another becomes increasingly difficult. What is the best solution for mobility? On a college campus, it's the bicycle. However, a bike alone won't solve any problems. Students need to use them, and the campus must be designed to accommodate cyclists.

I spoke with a friend who recently resumed cycling after a hiatus of several years. He mentioned he couldn't understand why he ever stopped. "Bikes are great," he said, "for a few years, it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it's the only way to get around." Besides being good for your body, cycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and some physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus, just as far from the campus center as some dorms. The smartest decision I made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have classes in the Thomas building, which is at least a 25-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can reduce that time to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only issue is that Pollock Road is the most direct route to the Thomas building from my house, and it's not always easy to travel on, with or without a bike. Walking has its advantages too, but personally, I'm too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable way to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day, totaling over two and a half hours every week. Adding the time spent walking to other classes and appointments would consume more time than I can afford.

Aldous Huxley, in his novel "Brave New World," critiques the looming threats of technology and the capitalistic framework by creating a dystopian world. In this world, people prioritize the collective over the individual and are conditioned from the start to seek immediate happiness. The citizens are shown to be mere pawns in a larger scheme, confined to a single ideology dictated by the World Controller. Analyzing the work through a Marxist lens reveals the author's underlying suspicions about the development of these systems. Terms often used in Marxism, like homogeneity and reification, support the idea that Huxley's novel comments on the flaws of the emerging economy of his time.

Capitalism is satirized through the Marxist concept of false consciousness. Essentially, ordinary citizens are kept from understanding their true economic relations with other classes, as they focus on their own gains. This is seen as a result of ideological control over the proletariat and common workers, something evident in how people are conditioned in "Brave New World." Common classes like Delta and Gamma have no true will of their own; through hypnopaedia, their drive to consume, spend, and indulge is greatly reinforced. This manipulation is, as previously mentioned, conducted by the World Controller. Hegemony, the idea that one group completely dominates social classes, is clearly applied here. The lower classes are entirely unaware of this manipulation, literally 'buying into an ideology that supports that structure' (i.e., capitalism and consumerism). The upper classes are born with the capacity to be aware but do nothing; few Alphas or Betas, beyond characters like Bernard, do much more than accept their place. The interactions among social classes, which will be further discussed, significantly highlight the perceived oppression of capitalism.

In "Brave New World," relationships between distinct individuals do not exist. The novel seemingly refuses to differentiate the characters—even major ones lack depth. Perhaps Huxley suggests that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprives humans of free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any single emotion; instead, interactions are kept superficial, illustrated through men's comments about women's physical appearance (like pneumatic quality) and women's candid remarks about their encounters. Furthermore, each societal class's complacency with their status in the hierarchy indicates the socioeconomic effects of capitalism. Their absolute obedience to their role in the community reflects Marxist thoughts on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and align with their peers.

Almost four years ago, I took a course on Islam at CBC. A main point of debate in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion, a question which I find more relevant now than ever. Since 9/11, I've noticed that the media's portrayal of Islam and its extremists shifted from hostility to extreme tolerance in America. Back in 2001, it seemed unlikely that a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, with clear Muslim roots in his family, could have emerged.

The biography of the Prophet fascinates me because it seems to contradict what I know about Muhammad's history. Previously, I believed Muhammad forced conversions to Islam by conquering tribes. Yet, the biography portrays him as a misunderstood martyr who humbled himself, leading people to embrace his teachings gradually.

There are also notable similarities between the ministries of Jesus and Muhammad's 'miracles', such as multiplying mutton and milk for over forty men. This writing style suggests the authors wanted Muhammad to be seen as a humble prophet, living in truth and miracles without needing to prove anything. This approach bothers me as it diminishes Jesus Christ's life and miracles, almost as if they're trying to attribute Jesus' life and persona to Muhammad.

Additionally, many stories in the biography seem to aim at providing proof of 'witnesses' or people 'independently' converting to Islam. However, these stories often come from third-party accounts, making them seem more suspicious despite intending to prove their truth.

What disturbs me most is the attempt to portray Muhammad as a godly, humble, and gentle man, as history contradicts this. I wonder if Muslims today are aware of the true history of Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and the beliefs he held during his lifetime were quickly left behind as Christian thought evolved after his life. Observing this history broadly, we see a trend of Christianity gradually straying from its origins. In today's world, there is an ever-growing awareness and unprecedented progressive tendencies. Although traditional people still exist and resist any thoughts beyond what they were taught, their numbers may not be sufficient to influence the whole. Among Christians, a historical awareness will grow significantly in the coming years. A desire will spread to distinguish doctrines that have been added to Christianity over time from the original intent of its founder. This may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome will be inevitable: there will be a major reversal in the trend of Christian history, returning to its original form. A movement will grow that will remove layers of doctrine, one by one, as if the clock is moving backward, until only the concept that Jesus introduced to humanity on behalf of God remains, without claims from other thinkers. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing many to worship in a way reminiscent of Jesus' time, following only his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead the way. However, as the theological clock moves backward, the extreme diversity within Christendom will reverse into greater uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, denominations, and various divisions, we will see fewer differences and increasing similarities. Human history is filled with great reversions. For example, Christians were once persecuted, shunned, and killed by the Roman Empire, but later that empire became a Christian institution. Our country has moved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The significant reversion in our future will play out in the Christian religion, undoing history in search of the source, and reducing diversity in the process. It is important to note that part of what will make this process possible is interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically, not literally. So what has happened since Jesus' lifetime? Looking far enough back in history, we find only Judaism, the theological starting point for Christianity. By the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were all central to the religion. The Jewish population did not share a single spirit. They were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the majority of common people.

The Jungle highlights the innate greed and selfishness of human nature. People care only about themselves, striving to improve their own lives while ignoring those beneath them. This is illustrated in many ways, particularly through the factory owners and managers who focus solely on expanding their enterprises. They disregard anyone or anything that stands in their way or suffers due to their progress. Upton Sinclair's work describes the stark silhouette of buildings against the sky, with smoke trailing like a river to the horizon, illustrating the immense harm caused by pollution. He shows that the owners are indifferent to the potential harm to people and animals, unconcerned about the smoke billowing from factories or the waste runoff from countless enclosures in Packingtown. The employers also show no concern for the workers who enrich them, doing anything to earn or save extra money. "From top to bottom, the place is a boiling pot of jealousy and hatred; there is no loyalty or decency, and no man is valued against a dollar." They force workers into long hours and can dismiss large numbers without notice or compensation. During the time The Jungle is set, few laws protected workers' safety or welfare, enabling managers and owners to act unchecked, pushing workers to accelerate progress under harsh conditions. Although not explicitly stated in the book, those who lived and worked themselves to death in Packingtown were expected to endure these conditions. There were no agencies to offer aid or information, and unions often exploited workers rather than helped them. The workers, trapped in this system, were likened to slaves, "a low-class, mostly foreign population, always on the brink of starvation, dependent on the whims of men as brutal as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is as inevitable and prevalent as under chattel slavery."

Dream-land is considered one of Edgar Allan Poe's better poems, according to his own assessment. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil, who referred to a northern island of Britain thought by the Greeks to be the edge of the known world. While Virgil did use this term, there is a more modern origin worth noting. Poe had a strong interest in German authors. This quote is significant because it demonstrates Poe's familiarity with Goethe's works. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," comments on the similarities between the two poems, concluding that Poe was imitating Goethe.

The "Oxford Companion to English Literature" describes Goethe as a celebrated writer of the poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second at the time of Goethe's death in 1832. Within the poetic verse of Faust's second part is a short poem titled "The King of Thulé." This poem tells of a king who begins drinking heavily and weeping after his wife's death, reminiscing about his lost queen. He decides it is time for him to die, leaving his possessions to his children except for the goblet. He then walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the sea, closes his eyes, and dies. The demeanor of the King of Thule and the description of the king in Dream-Land are very similar, possibly representing Poe's own sense of loss and reliance on drinking. Faust was also turned into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, less than a year before Poe used the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe references Thule twice in his collected writings. Once as "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," and twice in "Dream-Land," framing the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule as dark and lonely, haunted by dead friends, and perceives a shaded world without color. These scenes echo Goethe's "The King of Thule," where the king, having lost his wife, feels lonely and loses his will to rule or live. The entire poem feels as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's world.

Goethe was a significant author whom Poe would have known, even if only out of respect for Tennyson. Poe expressed his opinion when asked if he admired Tennyson. Beyond the connection to Tennyson, Poe would have encountered Goethe's work through the many adaptations following the original publication.

Under California law, can a customer injured after slipping on an applesauce spill in a grocery store be awarded punitive damages by proving the store manager acted with malice because he was informed twice about the spill and failed to clean it for half an hour due to being on a dinner break?

A judge is unlikely to immediately dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To justify such a claim, the plaintiff must show evidence that the defendant acted with willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm resulting from their conduct, and that the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have known the likely harm of not cleaning up the spill, as several D&D customers were injured from slipping in the months before Palmer's accident, yet he failed to clean it. While Palmer's argument that Martin's actions were despicable is less compelling, it remains reasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents occurred in 2009 and Martin still failed to take appropriate actions to ensure store safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, D&D Markets employee Rich Wayne informed his manager, Paul Martin, of an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne he was on a dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also informed Mr. Martin of the spill, and he responded the same way. At 5:30 pm on the 13th, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped on the spill and sustained a serious back injury. Before Palmer's accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising from a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." California Civil Code § 3294(a) defines malice as conduct intended to cause harm, or if absent intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and carried out with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when it is done with a conscious disregard of the plaintiff's rights, and the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Superior Court of Los Angeles County, 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She always felt like she needed something, a desire that was never fulfilled. This began when she was about 14, just stepping into her teenage years. Three years later, at 17, the feeling persisted. By then, she had realized she wanted someone rather than something. Yet, she had no interest in any boys. Some were attracted to her and awkwardly tried to win her over, but no one appealed to her. She often questioned herself about this unusual feeling, pondering what could cause such a strange phenomenon in a teenage girl. Her years of contemplation led to various theories, but none were convincing enough to explore further. So she continued living, constantly questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were kind and calm people. They never argued, and disagreements with their daughter were rare. The only thing they ever debated was her desire for independence and free expression. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, yet her lively and fun personality contrasted with their energy, making her very likable in combination with her kind nature.

Today, however, was not a calm day. As she moved from room to room searching for new inspiration, she heard a sudden scream from the kitchen, her mother's beautiful voice. She rushed in, panicking, and frantically asked, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the ground, appearing to be in pain, repeatedly saying "Ow" in short breaths. Her daughter ran to her side, trying to help. "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to the hospital." Her mother's words were rushed and strained, and her daughter could tell she was in great pain. "Okay, Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother guided her hands, and at that moment, the household hero was grateful for her strength training. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back seat, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought the smell of disinfectant and illness, tinged with fear. But she wasn't aware of it, as her mind was focused on helping her mother. She quickly brought the injured woman inside and called for help from the doctors. Several concerned faces gathered around, and someone swiftly brought in a rolling bed and placed her mother on it. They took her for immediate examination, leaving her daughter to sit and worry.

Her mother had fallen off a stepping stool while trying to reach a vase from the highest cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that adherence to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), indicated by a higher "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is associated with a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet, characterized by increased consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat), and fish, with reduced intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous prospective studies documented an inverse relationship between adherence to the Med diet and overall and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality risk. An intervention trial showed that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the total cholesterol to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ratio in obese individuals. Earlier studies did not focus specifically on stroke or stroke mortality.

The epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who were participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 U.S. states. From 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated the aMed diet score six times based on self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) to assess nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of the nurses continued participation throughout the 20-year period, and FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. When records were unavailable, cases were considered "probable" and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts classified in this way. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated for each FFQ, with leisure-time physical activity assessed beginning in 1986.

To reduce random variation for individuals and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from the two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors potentially affecting results) by accounting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between the aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. Over 20 years of follow-up, 2,391 incident cases of CHD, 1,763 incident cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (combined fatal CHD and strokes) were found. Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The sign claims that Hitler is alive in Burma.

Standing alone at a street corner, Ellen Page, the star of Juno, holds a piece of cardboard above her head with a disturbing message scrawled in marker. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation governed by a tyrannical military junta that seized power in a 1962 coup. In 2007, a series of street protests, the first in a decade, took place. Led by many Burmese monks, these protests became known as "The Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the monks' robes. Initially, the public began to take interest in the protests after the first few uprisings, and while the Burmese government reluctantly allowed the monks to hold peaceful gatherings at first, violence soon escalated into what some considered a full-blown conflict between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and looting monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were detained on sight, with a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai killed on September 27, 2007, simply for being present at a protest. Although the official death toll is listed as 13, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army days before the official report, stated, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities in our world, the desire of governments to suppress dissent and maintain total control over their citizens has existed as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors claimed to be chosen by the gods to have complete executive authority over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to be gods themselves, sent to lead their people to prosperity through inventions like Motorola phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, holds weekly calls with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary of the Republican Party.

Some well-known examples of such actions include the June 4, 1989, protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the government's authoritarian rule. The death toll for that particular event varies widely, with official Chinese government reports stating 200-300 dead, while the Chinese Red Cross reported 2,000-3,000 fatalities. Another example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began systematically killing all Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of ethnic background. Hitler’s 'Third Reich' is another extreme example, spanning several years and countries, where anyone of Jewish descent was rounded up and killed.

Duke Ellington's influence in jazz largely comes from his long career and his creative ability to shape his orchestra. While Ellington's presence on the piano is subtle in many of the compositions chosen for this assignment, he excelled as a composer in crafting rich and complex pieces that showcased the individual talents of his band members. He provided a framework for soloists to freely improvise, and also wrote tightly orchestrated pieces that utilized the unique styles of band members to highlight musical concepts. Through this, he emphasized the overall tone of the orchestra, creating cohesive and original sounds for each piece. Ellington's mastery of individual players’ sounds and how they fit into an expanding ensemble enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant works in jazz history. The Grove Music Dictionary, while discussing Ellington's sound and innovation, mentions "Creole Love Call" as an example of using voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This is an early example of his ability to add texture and color using voice without the constraints of lyrics. "Creole Love Call" also showcases Ellington's talent for complementing his soloists' styles, a skill evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece contains six choruses, structured as follows:  
Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, with the voice starting smooth and melodic, then shifting to a rougher tone.  
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo elaborating on the basic melody with emphasis on extended blue notes.  
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, supported by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.  
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with call and response between brass and reeds.  
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus where reeds begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop-time from brass and rhythm sections.  
Chorus 6: Returns to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice employs a "growl" technique, soloing as an instrument.  
Tag: A brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.  
Ellington's use of voice to add tonal color to this piece exemplifies a stylistic trait prevalent in his work.  
In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill in tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing uses vocal elements of Miley's playing and instrumental aspects of Cox's voice to create a rich, complementary sound. "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)" builds on these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a staple in his orchestra, to great effect by introducing the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve in the way they do? Are there any limitations or constraints that affect the direction of evolutionary change? Even though D'Arcy Thompson in 1917 remarked that "even now, the zoologist has scarcely begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," this statement still holds true today. Recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to the study of mollusk skeletogenesis through ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research is investigating how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can help clarify the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental changes. We used X-ray images of Prunum species to define quantitative parameters that could be used to simulate both hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were input into the software CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies to interpret the boundaries of possible morphological changes in Prunum. These findings are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be envisioned as a tubular structure that moves through 360 degrees of space over time. The turns or coils of a shell are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell, known as the columella. The rate at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last one (body whorl). The spire includes all whorls except the last one. The apex is the tip of the spire, while the opposite end is called the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be observed from apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the observer and the apex pointing upward.)

A method for counting whorls is shown below. First, the shell should be viewed from the apical view, and then the starting point of the first suture should be determined. A line is then drawn to divide the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that move through time and space as the animal builds its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture using the coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be represented graphically and mathematically. Once a mathematical formulation is established, it is possible to adjust parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

Over the past decade, the rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has remained relatively unchanged. Although the country is making progress toward achieving many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as those related to water and sanitation, the improvement rates in child and maternal health are significantly lagging behind what is needed to meet the 2015 targets. The various reasons for these deficiencies will be discussed below, highlighting the need to strengthen the health system rather than focusing solely on programmatic interventions. 

Indonesia has seen progress in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% of births now meeting this criterion. However, this statistic still encompasses traditional workers, such as midwives, who are unable to perform medical interventions in complicated pregnancies (hence the high rate of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage). Thus, the improvements in this indicator can be misleading, and there remains considerable work to be done. Additionally, there has been a decline in the percentage of children under five years with diarrhea being treated by a health professional. While data on postnatal care is incomplete, it is evident that this area also requires attention, as rates remain low nationwide.

Cesarean section rates are still lower than expected, around 4%. This rate further highlights a concerning issue: while urban areas have a c-section rate of 7%, rural areas have only 2%, underscoring the inequity of healthcare coverage across the country. Clearly, healthcare services are concentrated in urban regions. Another access issue concerns vertical equity, as there is a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles. The poor face significant challenges in accessing healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket expenses.

In discussing the next steps for improving neonatal and maternal care indicators, the fundamental question is how to effectively address the lack of services. Specifically, should Indonesia adopt targeted program-specific approaches or enhance the overall health system without focusing solely on pre and post-pregnancy care for mothers and children? Programmatic approaches to the problems outlined above can be appealing. "Vertical approaches," which focus on specific improvement areas, often have more defined, manageable objectives and generally yield quicker results. However, there are drawbacks to consider. A major issue is that heavy investment in one health sector area often means other areas suffer from reduced funding, and human resources tend to gravitate towards the better-funded area (the impact of international funding for HIV/AIDS on the family planning sector is one example). Additionally, running multiple parallel programs in one area results in service duplication that lacks coordination between programs, leading to increased paperwork for resources and funding.

Over the past century, the classification of popular music has broadened to encompass so many genres that listing them definitively is challenging. Adding complexity, most genres—like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—have spawned numerous sub-genres and even further subdivisions. In the last 40 years, Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres in popular music. It expresses a wide range of emotions, though it often gravitates towards darker themes. It is diverse because shortly after its inception, people recognized its flexibility and created sub-genres, which led to even more subdivisions, continuing to evolve today.

Currently, the heavy metal movement has branched into so many niches that defining heavy metal precisely is difficult. It has absorbed various themes from other genres, yet, like everything, it originated from somewhere. To truly understand today's metal music, one must first comprehend the essence of the metal movement and why it is seen as a movement rather than merely a genre.

Metal is in many ways a movement defined by darkness. It can be called the "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more intensity, more theatricality. With less primitiveness and more sophistication, musicians in metal bands excel in their craft, which is apparent in their music. Metal is also a movement heavily influenced by drugs, unsurprisingly. The psychedelic drug explosion in the mid-70s led to more outlandish creations, using drugs as a muse for otherworldly records. It holds many dark, visceral elements, which were new to the music scene since much popular music lacked darker emotional tones. Additionally, later metal generations have drawn from the dark, visceral elements of the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as those reflect the darkness that is central to the movement:

These lyrics from "Helter Skelter" showcase the Beatles' darker side. It mirrors a fluctuating experience, supposedly related to drugs. Some consider this song one of the first heavy metal tracks. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song with a similar heavy, dark tone. The Beatles aimed to prove they could match the Stones' heaviness, so they included it on The White Album.

A few decades before Surrealist artists began creating dreamlike paintings, Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, both in reality and metaphorically. His 1910 painting, "The Dream," by the renowned Post-Impressionist, showcases not only a woman marveling at the wonders of a dreamland but also reflects Rousseau's personal aspirations as a painter. From the start, he longed for recognition, acceptance, and praise from fellow artists and art lovers, finding himself in a challenging internal conflict to achieve these goals. "The Dream" epitomizes Rousseau's enduring struggle throughout his career: whether to conform to certain artistic styles to gain acceptance in the art world he cherished or to pursue creative autonomy and originality, charting his own course. Understanding Rousseau's biography is essential before analyzing "The Dream" from this perspective. Born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, northwestern France, Rousseau's father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who enjoyed "bourgeois prosperity" (Shattuck 47). Rousseau did not receive formal art education; instead, he worked until forty as a municipal toll service employee, mistakenly labeled a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). After the death of his first wife, Clémence, and eight infant children, Rousseau was left with one daughter, Julia, and deep sorrow (Shattuck 49). Seeking solace, he turned to painting for comfort and new beginnings. Unlike his contemporaries who romanticized peasants in art, Rousseau was essentially a folk painter, sharing hopes and dreams with his class's average member. His desire for acceptance in the art community is understandable in context: lacking formal training and starting his career late, he was creating amidst many talented and better-known modern artists. Although he worked for many years, proper recognition came only around the time Matisse was establishing his artistic reputation. In "Modern French Painters," Jan Gordon notes that while technically competitors, Rousseau and Matisse differed in style, subject, and reasons for painting: "Matisse feared painting in a clichéd way, whereas Rousseau aimed to create such a conventional piece that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français" (92).

Many great thinkers have suggested a close connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats says in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we learn in life comes from education or experience. However, as Keats implies, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics without needing to be taught in these expected ways. Both fields aim to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty largely attempt to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than providing a set of rules for judging or creating good art or moral behavior.

Moreover, criticism of art or morals never fully captures the essence of what is good or beautiful. For example, discussions about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might focus on concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately these do not describe why it is good art. Instead, when asked about a favorite piece of art or literature, one often hears something like, "There's just something about it," before a more detailed explanation. I believe both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." No matter how thoroughly we describe the properties of a literary work, something transcendent remains. I believe ethics shares this quality. As Wittgenstein says, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental."
